The United States and the European Union have reached an agreement on steel and aluminum tariffs. The deal allows limited volumes of EU steel and aluminum to enter the US tariff-free while maintaining the 232 tariffs. The agreement also includes provisions to fight global excess capacity, address carbon intensity, and drop retaliatory tariffs. The deal is seen as a step forward in addressing the challenges of climate change and unfair competition posed by China. It is aimed at protecting American industries, reducing costs for manufacturers and consumers, and creating a framework for future negotiations on carbon intensity. The agreement is considered a significant achievement and a demonstration of the Biden administration's commitment to strengthening alliances and addressing key global challenges.